a images not only reflect the national mood but also play a powerful role in shaping national discourse. Drawing on insights from anthropology, sociology, and cultural studies, this original and perceptive book raises new questions about the media's influence over the public's increasing fear of immigration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 4aCultural Studies. 4aanthropology. 4adebate. 4aethnic studies. 4aimmigration. 4amedia. 4amigration. 4aminorities. 4anation. 4apublic. 4asociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520925250?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520925250423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520925250/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles